e in Nord, France, married Anne Mabille in Quebec City, QC, <i>c.</i> 1666."]},{"name":"Salt","meanings":["English: habitational name from Salt (Staffordshire), from Old English <i>selte</i> ‘salt pit’. Occasionally the name may be a nickname for a producer or seller of salt, from Middle English <i>salt</i> ‘salt’ (compare   Salter  ), but evidence is lacking.","Native American (Navajo): from a translation into English of the name of the Navajo clan <i>Áshįįhi</i> ‘Salt People’."]},{"name":"Saulter","meanings":["English: variant of   Salter  ."]},{"name":"Saltman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): occupational name for a producer or seller of salt, from Middle English <i>salt</i> ‘salt’ + <i>-man</i>. See also   Salter  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Salzmann   or Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Saltsman  , or of their rare German cognate <b>Saltmann</b>."]},{"name":"Souter","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>souter(e)</i>, <i>suter(e)</i> ‘shoemaker, cobbler’ (Old English <i>sūtere</i>, from Latin <i>sūtor</i>, an agent derivative of <i>suere</i> ‘to sew’). In early Modern English, pronunciation of the name would regularly develop from /su:ter/ to /sautə(r)/ (rhyming with <i>outer</i>), or to /sutə(r)/, as in   Sutter  . In Scots, however, it remained unchanged, with the spelling <i>-ou-</i> representing /u/. In parts of southern England it seems also to have remained as /u:/; see   Suter   (2).","Americanized form of German   Sauter  , a cognate of 1 above.","Flemish (<b>De Souter</b>): occupational name for a producer or seller of salt, from an agent derivative of Middle Dutch <i>sout</i> ‘salt’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Salter was born about 1335, in Oswestry, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Anne Kiffen about 1369, in Oswestry,